1
00:00:04,063 --> 00:00:05,063
(Sponsors: The Ministry of Culture, Sports and Tourism...)

2
00:00:05,063 --> 00:00:06,063
(and Korea Creative Content Agency)

3
00:00:07,963 --> 00:00:09,533
This is King Sejong Station.

4
00:00:10,303 --> 00:00:12,003
(Actually, we were in serious danger.)

5
00:00:12,703 --> 00:00:16,043
(The waves are rough, and the weather suddenly shifts.)

6
00:00:16,573 --> 00:00:21,013
(2 hours ago)

7
00:00:21,283 --> 00:00:25,383
(The crew members are busy preparing the food.)

8
00:00:25,983 --> 00:00:27,152
It was an uneasy feeling.

9
00:00:27,153 --> 00:00:29,353
I could see the weather outside the window while cooking.

10
00:00:30,353 --> 00:00:31,793
I kept observing while working in the kitchen.

11
00:00:35,323 --> 00:00:36,823
I was anxious. The snow...

12
00:00:38,393 --> 00:00:41,402
At first, I just thought, "I guess we are in Antarctica after all."

13
00:00:41,403 --> 00:00:44,203
But the snow grew heavier and began striking the windows.

14
00:00:44,733 --> 00:00:46,233
Gosh, it's snowing pretty hard.

15
00:00:46,973 --> 00:00:49,073
It's windy too. The snow is blowing horizontally.

16
00:00:49,273 --> 00:00:51,073
At first, I thought, "What a beautiful sight."

17
00:00:51,713 --> 00:00:55,983
"I guess we're lucky to see some snow in Antarctica."

18
00:00:56,913 --> 00:00:58,583
But as time went on, the snowflakes got thicker.

19
00:00:59,083 --> 00:01:00,112
And it snowed harder.

20
00:01:00,113 --> 00:01:03,083
All of a sudden, I got scared.

21
00:01:04,153 --> 00:01:05,553
Oh, my. It's very windy.

22
00:01:06,793 --> 00:01:08,363
(Worried)

23
00:01:08,963 --> 00:01:10,663
My goodness. The wind is quite strong.

24
00:01:11,993 --> 00:01:13,602
(As the weather worsens, )

25
00:01:13,603 --> 00:01:15,162
(people outside the kitchen also become busy.)

26
00:01:15,163 --> 00:01:16,403
What on earth is going on?

27
00:01:17,673 --> 00:01:19,833
Look over there. The flag is about to get ripped away.

28
00:01:20,773 --> 00:01:26,983
(They suddenly find themselves in rapidly worsening weather.)

29
00:01:29,543 --> 00:01:32,782
(The weather worsens to the point...)

30
00:01:32,783 --> 00:01:36,683
(where visibility disappears.)

31
00:01:37,293 --> 00:01:39,452
(With the weather crisis unfolding, )

32
00:01:39,453 --> 00:01:41,623
(the production crew and crew members gather in private.)

33
00:01:42,123 --> 00:01:44,132
Sir, the wind is very strong.

34
00:01:44,133 --> 00:01:45,693
And the tides are very poor.

35
00:01:46,793 --> 00:01:48,303
I suggest no sail.

36
00:01:48,863 --> 00:01:49,933
It won't be safe.

37
00:01:51,833 --> 00:01:53,943
Leader Lee, this is Kwon Young Hoon.

38
00:01:54,303 --> 00:01:57,213
(Secretary Kwon updates the station with the latest news.)

39
00:01:57,543 --> 00:02:00,613
The waves are too high. We're turning back.

40
00:02:00,713 --> 00:02:02,312
It'll be absolutely impossible...

41
00:02:02,313 --> 00:02:04,482
to sail on the boat against these waves.

42
00:02:04,483 --> 00:02:06,413
Anyway, it's impossible because it's too dangerous.

43
00:02:06,783 --> 00:02:09,352
- I understood.
- Okay.

44
00:02:09,353 --> 00:02:10,893
(He finishes his radio call with the leader at the station.)

45
00:02:12,293 --> 00:02:13,293
(Afterward, )

46
00:02:13,294 --> 00:02:15,762
(an emergency contingency meeting was held immediately.)

47
00:02:15,763 --> 00:02:19,292
When we were leaving this morning, the weather forecast seemed okay.

48
00:02:19,293 --> 00:02:21,302
But the weather is taking...

49
00:02:21,303 --> 00:02:23,533
a worse turn than we expected.

50
00:02:24,673 --> 00:02:27,143
As you can see out the windows,

51
00:02:29,243 --> 00:02:30,942
the wind speed is at 15m per second.

52
00:02:30,943 --> 00:02:33,273
(Current wind speed: 15m per second)

53
00:02:34,413 --> 00:02:37,753
According to the safety policy, when it goes over 10m per second,

54
00:02:38,683 --> 00:02:39,812
(Boats can't be operated.)

55
00:02:39,813 --> 00:02:42,122
boats can't be operated.

56
00:02:42,123 --> 00:02:43,623
- That's the policy.
- What do we do?

57
00:02:44,453 --> 00:02:46,222
If we were to try to power through...

58
00:02:46,223 --> 00:02:47,962
and return to King Sejong Station in this blizzard,

59
00:02:47,963 --> 00:02:50,193
we might end up dead.

60
00:02:50,763 --> 00:02:51,763
So has it been decided?

61
00:02:51,833 --> 00:02:55,903
We looked at the data from our station and the Chinese Station.

62
00:02:56,003 --> 00:02:59,202
If anything, the weather could only get worse.

63
00:02:59,203 --> 00:03:01,143
We doubt that its conditions would improve.

64
00:03:01,703 --> 00:03:03,943
After analyzing the situation from different angles,

65
00:03:04,173 --> 00:03:06,743
we believe that returning to our station will be impossible.

66
00:03:07,883 --> 00:03:10,952
I wasn't sure if it was actually happening or a prank.

67
00:03:10,953 --> 00:03:12,913
I was so flustered I couldn't make sense of anything.

68
00:03:13,453 --> 00:03:15,023
Honestly, I couldn't believe it was happening.

69
00:03:15,683 --> 00:03:17,753
I was a bit scared.

70
00:03:19,293 --> 00:03:20,322
This is the worst.

71
00:03:20,323 --> 00:03:21,392
(As no one saw this coming, )

72
00:03:21,393 --> 00:03:23,162
Everything about this situation is just terrible.

73
00:03:23,163 --> 00:03:24,533
(they are confused.)

74
00:03:24,593 --> 00:03:26,392
This doesn't affect just us.

75
00:03:26,393 --> 00:03:28,133
It affects the production crew too. That's over 20 people.

76
00:03:28,233 --> 00:03:32,533
Including the production crew, there are 29 of us here.

77
00:03:33,433 --> 00:03:38,012
So due to these reasons, could you ask him...

78
00:03:38,013 --> 00:03:41,642
if there would be a problem for all 29 of us to stay...

79
00:03:41,643 --> 00:03:44,553
at this station? Could you check that again?

80
00:03:45,253 --> 00:03:47,822
Could all of our staff stay? We're 29 people.

81
00:03:47,823 --> 00:03:49,552
(Otherwise, the crew members of Antarctica...)

82
00:03:49,553 --> 00:03:51,322
(will have to walk in the blizzard to another station.)

83
00:03:51,323 --> 00:03:52,952
- Is there any problem?
- Today?

84
00:03:52,953 --> 00:03:53,963
Yes.

85
00:03:59,893 --> 00:04:01,062
- No problem.
- No problem.

86
00:04:01,063 --> 00:04:04,703
(Giving permission within 0.1 seconds)

87
00:04:05,073 --> 00:04:08,302
(Their generosity makes the crew members smile...)

88
00:04:08,303 --> 00:04:10,142
(without any concern.)

89
00:04:10,143 --> 00:04:11,143
Don't worry.

90
00:04:11,143 --> 00:04:12,143
(Don't worry about anything.)

91
00:04:12,143 --> 00:04:13,143
- Don't worry.
- Thank you.

92
00:04:13,673 --> 00:04:14,942
Seriously. This is crazy.

93
00:04:14,943 --> 00:04:18,753
We came here to cook for them because they've done a lot...

94
00:04:18,853 --> 00:04:21,023
- for our station.
- Right.

95
00:04:21,383 --> 00:04:23,483
No way. We owe them another one.

96
00:04:23,653 --> 00:04:25,592
- Luckily, they will let us stay.
- Yes.

97
00:04:25,593 --> 00:04:27,022
- They said we could stay.
- Yes. They did.

98
00:04:27,023 --> 00:04:28,423
That's a relief, for sure.

99
00:04:28,763 --> 00:04:32,732
I think we'll have many chances to go to Korea.

100
00:04:32,733 --> 00:04:36,202
And you will also have many chances to visit China...

101
00:04:36,203 --> 00:04:38,132
because we're neighbors.

102
00:04:38,133 --> 00:04:42,273
So I welcome everyone to our station.

103
00:04:43,043 --> 00:04:45,913
- Thank you.
- Thank you.

104
00:04:46,013 --> 00:04:47,713
No worries. It's my pleasure.

105
00:04:47,813 --> 00:04:49,313
You saved our lives.

106
00:04:50,683 --> 00:04:53,953
(Thanks to them, they can finally relax.)

107
00:04:54,123 --> 00:04:56,283
They gladly took us in.

108
00:04:56,383 --> 00:04:58,023
I'm very grateful to them.

109
00:04:58,693 --> 00:05:00,663
We could've frozen to death outside.

110
00:05:00,763 --> 00:05:03,323
I'm really relieved that they let us spend the night.

111
00:05:04,433 --> 00:05:07,232
The weather conditions keep on changing.

112
00:05:07,233 --> 00:05:08,362
- I'll keep in touch...
- Keep talking to them.

113
00:05:08,363 --> 00:05:09,502
with our station.

114
00:05:09,503 --> 00:05:11,932
- I should pray.
- If we see any improvement...

115
00:05:11,933 --> 00:05:13,702
- in the weather conditions, - Let's hurry up then.

116
00:05:13,703 --> 00:05:15,542
we'll try to head back.

117
00:05:15,543 --> 00:05:17,372
To do that, we'll stay prepared.

118
00:05:17,373 --> 00:05:18,542
(They will communicate and try to return to the station.)

119
00:05:18,543 --> 00:05:19,613
- Thank you.
- Thanks.

120
00:05:20,783 --> 00:05:25,053
(The emergency meeting is over.)

121
00:05:29,283 --> 00:05:32,053
(They can't seem to leave the table.)

122
00:05:32,253 --> 00:05:33,753
We should be happy.

123
00:05:33,863 --> 00:05:36,823
But we were isolated without having prepared anything.

124
00:05:38,193 --> 00:05:39,992
(The crew members came unprepared for this possibility.)

125
00:05:39,993 --> 00:05:41,563
I didn't bring anything.

126
00:05:41,663 --> 00:05:42,763
I'm in big trouble.

127
00:05:43,333 --> 00:05:44,732
Could you ask...

128
00:05:44,733 --> 00:05:46,503
if they have contact lens solution and a container?

129
00:05:46,933 --> 00:05:49,673
None of us thought, "We might end up sleeping over."

130
00:05:50,473 --> 00:05:52,813
"We should bring some toner and lotion."

131
00:05:53,443 --> 00:05:56,243
It was our first time experiencing capricious weather in Antarctica.

132
00:05:56,343 --> 00:05:57,513
My first concern was,

133
00:05:58,113 --> 00:06:00,013
"We might not be able to return tomorrow even."

134
00:06:00,483 --> 00:06:02,122
"Or the day after tomorrow."

135
00:06:02,123 --> 00:06:04,123
"What if we end up isolated here for 2 to 3 days?"

136
00:06:04,993 --> 00:06:05,993
I wasn't scared or anything.

137
00:06:05,994 --> 00:06:09,192
I was mostly concerned about meals for our crew back at the station.

138
00:06:09,193 --> 00:06:10,293
That's what worried me.

139
00:06:12,563 --> 00:06:14,062
- Gosh.
- Oh, my. It's so cold.

140
00:06:14,063 --> 00:06:15,263
(The crew members head over to their accomodation.)

141
00:06:16,333 --> 00:06:17,733
Oh, my. The weather is a complete change from this morning.

142
00:06:17,933 --> 00:06:19,902
- Right. This is unbelievable.
- It's cold.

143
00:06:19,903 --> 00:06:20,903
(Surprised by experiencing the weather change firsthand)

144
00:06:21,303 --> 00:06:25,372
(When arriving at the Chinese Station, the weather was clear.)

145
00:06:25,373 --> 00:06:27,783
The weather kept changing minute by minute.

146
00:06:28,743 --> 00:06:30,512
My gosh, it was no joke.

147
00:06:30,513 --> 00:06:32,113
(The station is covered in snow within a short period of time.)

148
00:06:32,553 --> 00:06:35,453
I was too busy cooking. I didn't think about the weather.

149
00:06:37,523 --> 00:06:38,523
It changed so quickly.

150
00:06:38,524 --> 00:06:41,123
(It's shocking how quickly the weather changed.)

151
00:06:42,293 --> 00:06:46,363
(Will they be able to return tomorrow?)

152
00:06:48,403 --> 00:06:53,703
(The unexpected night out of their station begins.)

153
00:06:55,103 --> 00:06:58,913
(Soo Hyang is resting in her room.)

154
00:06:59,213 --> 00:07:02,042
I'll tell you where you can use hot water. Here.

155
00:07:02,043 --> 00:07:05,612
(Crew: 37.8, Name: Im Soo Hyang)

156
00:07:05,613 --> 00:07:07,212
- I see.
- You can drink water here.

157
00:07:07,213 --> 00:07:10,053
- We have cold and hot water.
- Hot water.

158
00:07:10,553 --> 00:07:11,593
Thank you.

159
00:07:11,693 --> 00:07:13,823
If you need snacks, you can take everything.

160
00:07:15,423 --> 00:07:17,763
If you like, you can take everything. Okay?

161
00:07:18,163 --> 00:07:20,432
Thank you. You're so sweet.

162
00:07:20,433 --> 00:07:21,533
(Leader Wang looks after her in case she feels awkward.)

163
00:07:22,233 --> 00:07:25,173
- Hello.
- Do you want to play PlayStation?

164
00:07:25,273 --> 00:07:29,602
Gosh. Yes. But later, maybe.

165
00:07:29,603 --> 00:07:31,173
I'm quite tired now.

166
00:07:31,913 --> 00:07:33,272
- Thank you.
- Later.

167
00:07:33,273 --> 00:07:34,343
Later, thank you.

168
00:07:35,213 --> 00:07:36,612
I'm grateful that...

169
00:07:36,613 --> 00:07:39,082
(Crew: 37.8, Name: SUHO)

170
00:07:39,083 --> 00:07:40,653
The Chinese Station let us sleep here.

171
00:07:41,023 --> 00:07:43,323
I'll get a good night of rest here and then go back.

172
00:07:47,023 --> 00:07:49,122
(Due to this unexpected situation, )

173
00:07:49,123 --> 00:07:51,232
(the production crew will spend the night here too.)

174
00:07:51,233 --> 00:07:52,693
Be careful. There's a lot of glass.

175
00:07:53,063 --> 00:07:55,433
- It's colder in this corner.
- The bathroom is...

176
00:07:58,903 --> 00:08:03,403
(We truly felt the warmth and care from our neighbor in Antarctica.)

177
00:08:05,813 --> 00:08:13,213
(The night of the blizzard passes.)

178
00:08:14,383 --> 00:08:22,323
(The sky clears up magically as the sun rises.)

179
00:08:36,273 --> 00:08:39,413
(The next morning)

180
00:08:41,083 --> 00:08:45,013
(The crew members set out to return to King Sejong Station.)

181
00:08:45,483 --> 00:08:47,052
Thank you, sir.

182
00:08:47,053 --> 00:08:49,883
- Thank you.
- Don't mention it. We're friends.

183
00:08:52,353 --> 00:08:56,193
The blizzard disappeared as if it were never here.

184
00:08:56,563 --> 00:08:57,563
Right.

185
00:08:57,564 --> 00:08:59,263
(While they put on a life jacket, )

186
00:09:00,263 --> 00:09:03,703
(boats arrive one after another.)

187
00:09:05,103 --> 00:09:06,273
Move slowly.

188
00:09:07,673 --> 00:09:10,942
(As they bonded overnight, they're sad to say goodbye.)

189
00:09:10,943 --> 00:09:12,312
Everyone came out.

190
00:09:12,313 --> 00:09:14,743
(It's already time to say goodbye.)

191
00:09:15,343 --> 00:09:17,583
- Thank you for coming.
- Thank you.

192
00:09:17,753 --> 00:09:19,383
Thank you so much.

193
00:09:19,983 --> 00:09:22,253
We came to repay your kindness, but we owe you once again.

194
00:09:23,023 --> 00:09:24,823
We were going to give you this yesterday.

195
00:09:25,523 --> 00:09:28,122
This is a bell that brings good luck.

196
00:09:28,123 --> 00:09:32,093
We have a souvenir from our show. You like souvenirs, right?

197
00:09:32,893 --> 00:09:33,932
It's a small present.

198
00:09:33,933 --> 00:09:34,962
(It's a small present.)

199
00:09:34,963 --> 00:09:37,532
Can you hear the bell? It brings good luck.

200
00:09:37,533 --> 00:09:38,632
(But it comes with love and care.)

201
00:09:38,633 --> 00:09:39,773
- Thank you.
- Thank you.

202
00:09:40,333 --> 00:09:42,143
If a good opportunity arises, I'll see you again. Thanks.

203
00:09:42,603 --> 00:09:44,213
- Everybody, are you okay?
- Thank you.

204
00:09:44,313 --> 00:09:46,212
- Goodbye.
- Thank you.

205
00:09:46,213 --> 00:09:47,512
(Everyone shakes hands to say goodbye.)

206
00:09:47,513 --> 00:09:48,713
Thank you.

207
00:09:50,243 --> 00:09:51,282
Take care.

208
00:09:51,283 --> 00:09:53,583
- Yes. You too. Take care.
- Yes. Take care.

209
00:09:53,783 --> 00:09:55,352
- Thank you.
- Thank you.

210
00:09:55,353 --> 00:09:56,552
(With heavy hearts, they head back to the station.)

211
00:09:56,553 --> 00:09:57,553
Thank you.

212
00:09:58,453 --> 00:09:59,593
You're welcome anytime.

213
00:10:00,723 --> 00:10:02,022
All right.

214
00:10:02,023 --> 00:10:03,193
(Leaping onto the boat energetically)

215
00:10:04,993 --> 00:10:07,763
(The crew members of Antarctica are ready to set sail.)

216
00:10:08,133 --> 00:10:09,863
Take care!

217
00:10:09,963 --> 00:10:11,902
- Take care.
- Bye!

218
00:10:11,903 --> 00:10:16,073
(Take care of yourselves too!)

219
00:10:17,143 --> 00:10:18,213
Bye, Li!

220
00:10:19,173 --> 00:10:20,313
We're setting out.

221
00:10:23,713 --> 00:10:27,522
(Just as they welcomed us when we first arrived, )

222
00:10:27,523 --> 00:10:31,593
(the Chinese crew members are sending us off wholeheartedly.)

223
00:10:33,493 --> 00:10:36,422
(Out of gratitude, the crew members of Antarctica...)

224
00:10:36,423 --> 00:10:39,363
(wave at them until they can't see the Chinese crew anymore.)

225
00:10:41,533 --> 00:10:43,802
(They slowly sail away from the Chinese crew...)

226
00:10:43,803 --> 00:10:46,073
(with whom they bonded overnight.)

227
00:10:46,603 --> 00:10:50,473
(Capturing the unforgettable moment)

228
00:10:52,613 --> 00:10:55,043
They helped us out a lot. So the experience taught me this.

229
00:10:55,683 --> 00:10:57,512
The stations have to rely on each other...

230
00:10:57,513 --> 00:10:59,713
in case they get isolated.

231
00:11:00,013 --> 00:11:01,083
I wanted to help them in any way.

232
00:11:01,683 --> 00:11:03,053
We had to rely on each other.

233
00:11:03,253 --> 00:11:04,353
It was a great experience.

234
00:11:05,323 --> 00:11:08,963
When I was cooking a meal for the crew members,

235
00:11:09,263 --> 00:11:11,732
I wanted them to feel well-treated...

236
00:11:11,733 --> 00:11:14,562
as they enjoyed our food.

237
00:11:14,563 --> 00:11:17,833
I wanted them to feel a sense of warmth through the meal.

238
00:11:17,933 --> 00:11:19,932
That crossed my mind.

239
00:11:19,933 --> 00:11:21,202
(Treating them with a meal, prepared wholeheartedly)

240
00:11:21,203 --> 00:11:23,703
We couldn't return on the same day due to the weather conditions.

241
00:11:23,803 --> 00:11:27,143
But the Chinese crew gladly offered us a place to stay for the night.

242
00:11:27,243 --> 00:11:30,283
They said they had tasty food, so we could ask for it anytime.

243
00:11:31,813 --> 00:11:33,013
It was a special experience.

244
00:11:35,823 --> 00:11:40,392
(They take a good look at the station one last time.)

245
00:11:40,393 --> 00:11:42,323
Doesn't it feel like we're going home?

246
00:11:45,393 --> 00:11:49,003
(The crew members go back home.)

247
00:11:50,403 --> 00:11:53,433
(Looking around)

248
00:11:53,733 --> 00:11:55,203
That's King Sejong Station, right?

249
00:11:56,573 --> 00:11:57,913
- Is that it?
- Yes.

250
00:11:58,113 --> 00:11:59,142
It's quite close.

251
00:11:59,143 --> 00:12:01,043
(Before they knew it, King Sejong Station came into view.)

252
00:12:02,183 --> 00:12:05,583
Communication room. This is Sejong 12.

253
00:12:06,853 --> 00:12:08,953
Sejong 12. Go ahead.

254
00:12:10,683 --> 00:12:13,392
Im Soo Hyang and eleven crew members are returning...

255
00:12:13,393 --> 00:12:15,463
to the station on Sejung 12 now.

256
00:12:15,963 --> 00:12:17,493
We'll arrive in five minutes.

257
00:12:18,933 --> 00:12:20,732
Five minutes before the arrival of Soo Hyang...

